{"id":"1604.00919","submitter":"Benoit Girard","authors":"Charles Thurat (ISIR), Steve N 'Guyen (LPPA, ISIR), Beno\\^it Girard\n  (ISIR)","title":"Biomimetic race model of the loop between the superior colliculus and\n  the basal ganglia: Subcortical selection of saccade targets","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Neural Networks, Elsevier, 2015, 67, pp.54-73","doi":"10.1016/j.neunet.2015.02.004","report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.NC q-bio.MN","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Superior Colliculus, a laminar structure involved in the retinotopic\nmapping of the visual field, plays a cardinal role in the several cortical and\nsubcortical loops of the saccadic system. Although the selection of saccade\ntargets has long been thought to be the sole product of cortical processes, a\ngrowing body of evidence hints at the implication of the Superior Colliculus,\nfirstly by the lateral connections between the neurons of its maps, and\nsecondly by its interactions with the midbrain Basal Ganglia, already renowned\nfor their role in decision making. We propose a biomimetic population-coded\nrace model of selection based on a dynamic tecto-basal loop that reproduces the\nobserved ability of the Superior Colliculus to stochastically select between\nsimilar stimuli, the accuracy of this selection depending on the\ndiscriminability of the target and the distractors. Our model also offers an\nexplanation for the phenomenon of Remote Distractor Effect based on the lateral\nconnectivity within the Basal Ganglia circuitry rather than on lateral\ninhibitions within the collicular maps. Finally, we propose a role for the\nintermediate layers of the Superior Colliculus, as stochastic integrators\ndynamically gated by the selective disinhibition of the Basal Ganglia channels\nthat is consistent with the recorded activity profiles of these neurons.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 2 Sep 2015 08:48:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-04-05"}
